#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/lena/skills/marketing-and-growth/cold-email/references/subject-lines.md
M|references|The subject line determines whether the email gets read. The data is counterintuitive: **short, boring, internal-looking subject lines win decisively.**
M|references|- 2-word subject lines get **60% more opens** than 5-word (Lavender).
M|references|- Going from 2 to 4 words reduces replies by **17.5%**.
M|references|- 2–4 words yield **46% open rates** vs 34% for 10 words (Belkins, 5.5M emails).
M|references|- Mobile truncates at 30–35 characters — brevity is practical necessity.
M|references|Subject lines that look like they came from a colleague, not a vendor, double open rates (Gong). Buyers mentally categorize before opening — if it looks like sales, it's filtered.
M|references|**High-performing examples:** "reply rates" · "trial delays" · "hiring ops" · "employee turnover" · "Q2 forecast" · "new patients" · "personalization issue" · "second page"
M|references|All-lowercase has highest open rates (Gong, 85M+ emails). Lowercase looks more personal/internal. For cold outreach specifically, lowercase beats title case.
M|references|Personalized subject lines boost opens **26–50%**, but type matters:
M|references|- **First name in subject line → 12% fewer replies.** Signals automation.
M|references|- **Contextual personalization works:** pain points, cp, trigger events, industry challenges.
M|references|- Use {{painPoint}}, {{cp}}, {{commonGround}} — not {{firstName}}.
M|references|Data conflicts: Belkins says questions perform well (46% open rate). Lavender says questions lower opens by **56%**. Resolution: **specific pain questions work** ("Need help with {{challenge}}?"), **g
M|references|| Anti-pattern                                   | Impact                      |
M|references|| ---------------------------------------------- | --------------------------- |
M|references|| Salesy language ("increase," "boost," "ROI")   | -17.9% opens                |
M|references|| Urgency words ("ASAP," "urgent")               | Below 36% opens             |
M|references|| Excessive punctuation ("!!!" or "??")          | -36% opens                  |
M|references|| Numbers and percentages                        | -46% opens                  |
M|references|| Emojis                                         | Hurt B2B professionalism    |
M|references|| Pitching product in subject                    | -57% replies                |
M|references|| Empty/no subject line                          | +30% opens but -12% replies |
M|references|| Spam triggers ("free," "guarantee," "act now") | Deliverability risk         |
M|references|Executives receive 300–400 emails daily, decide in seconds. They respond **23% more often** than non-C-suite when emails pass their filter (6.4% reply rate).
M|references|What works: ultra-concise, human, understated. "{{companyInitiative}}" · "thank you" · "an update" · "a question" · reference to a specific project or trigger event.
M|references|Anything "salesy" is immediately rejected.